## Design decisions worth calling out

| Decision | Why |
|---|---|
| **`Map<ip, number[]>` (sorted ascending)** | Appending is O(1); the window always slides from the front. No need to sort. |
| **Binary search for the cutoff** | `firstValidIndex` is O(log n) rather than a linear scan — meaningfully faster when a high-traffic IP accumulates hundreds of in-window stamps. |
| **`slideWindow` returns the same reference when nothing was trimmed** | Avoids a heap allocation on the hot path for clients well under the limit. |
| **`.unref()` on the cleanup timer** | The process won't hang in test suites or after `server.close()` just because the 60 s interval hasn't fired yet. `close()` is a belt-and-suspenders guarantee for environments that don't support `.unref()`. |
| **`X-RateLimit-Reset` = oldest-timestamp + windowMs** | For a sliding window there is no single "reset time"; the natural analogue is when the first occupied slot opens up — the earliest the client can gain one more request even at full-speed hammering. |
| **`retryAfter` via `live[0]` not `now + windowMs`** | `now + windowMs` would over-estimate; the actual first slot opens when the *oldest* in-window request ages out, which could be much sooner than a full window from now. |

